Certainly! Here's the code in ExcelJS to validate blanks and create a dynamic drop-down list without blank cells:

```javascript
// Load ExcelJS module
const ExcelJS = require('exceljs');

// Load the workbook
const workbook = new ExcelJS.Workbook();

// Load the worksheet
workbook.xlsx.readFile('path/to/workbook.xlsx').then(() => {
  const worksheet = workbook.getWorksheet('Sheet1');

  // Data validation to filter blanks
  const columnToValidate = worksheet.getColumn('A');

  columnToValidate.eachCell((cell, rowNumber) => {
     if (!cell.value) {
       worksheet.getCell(`A${rowNumber}`).dataValidation = {
         type: 'error',
         error: 'Blank cells are not allowed.',
         showErrorMessage: true,
       };
     }
  });

  // Create dynamic named range without blank cells
  const namedRange = worksheet.names.add({
    name: 'MyList',
    reference: `=OFFSET(Sheet1!$A$1,0,0,COUNTA(Sheet1!$A:$A),1)`,
  });

  // Set the Data Validation Range
  const dataValidationRange = worksheet.getCell('B2');

  dataValidationRange.dataValidation = {
    type: 'list',
    allowBlank: false,
    formulae: [namedRange], 
  };

  // Save the workbook
  return workbook.xlsx.writeFile('path/to/workbook.xlsx');
}).then(() => {
  console.log('Workbook saved successfully!');
}).catch((error) => {
  console.log(error);
});
```

Replace `path/to/workbook.xlsx` with the path to your existing workbook. This code validates the column to filter out blank cells and creates a dynamic named range without blank cells. It also sets the data validation range to use the named range as a drop-down list.

