I apologize for the error. It seems that using `worksheet.names` is not supported in some versions of ExcelJS. Here's the updated code to create a named range without using `worksheet.names`:

```javascript
// Load ExcelJS module
const ExcelJS = require('exceljs');

// Load the workbook
const workbook = new ExcelJS.Workbook();

// Load the worksheet
workbook.xlsx.readFile('path/to/workbook.xlsx').then(() => {
  const worksheet = workbook.getWorksheet('Sheet1');

  // Data validation to filter blanks
  const columnToValidate = worksheet.getColumn('A');

  columnToValidate.eachCell((cell, rowNumber) => {
    if (!cell.value) {
      worksheet.getCell(`A${rowNumber}`).dataValidation = {
        type: 'error',
        error: 'Blank cells are not allowed.',
        showErrorMessage: true,
      };
    }
  });

  // Create dynamic named range without blank cells
  const range = worksheet.findCell('A1');
  const lastRow = worksheet.rowCount;
  const lastColumn = worksheet.columnCount;

  const namedRange = `${range.address}:${worksheet.getColumn(lastColumn).letter}${lastRow}`;
  worksheet.addDataValidation(`B2:B1000`, {
    type: 'list',
    allowBlank: false,
    formulae: [`=${namedRange}`],
  });

  // Save the workbook
  return workbook.xlsx.writeFile('path/to/workbook.xlsx');
}).then(() => {
  console.log('Workbook saved successfully!');
}).catch((error) => {
  console.log(error);
});
```

This code creates the named range by finding the first cell of the column to validate and the last cell that contains data in the worksheet. You can modify the code to suit your needs by changing the sheet name, the column to validate and the range of cells where the drop-down list should appear.

